"Millet D.B., Atlas E.L., Blake D.R., Blake N.J., Diskin G.S., Holloway J.S., Hudman R.C., Meinardi S., Ryerson T.B., Sachse G.W.","Halocarbon emissions from the United States and Mexico and their global warming potential",2009,"Environmental Science and Technology","43","4",,"1055","1060",,,10.1021/es802146j,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-64349099997&partnerID=40&md5=f10b825095f4a3fb4b26855de4f15e10","University of Minnesota, St. Paul, MN 55108, United States; University of Miami, Miami, FL 33149, United States; University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States; NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; NOAA, CSD, Boulder, CO 80305, United States; University of California, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States","Millet, D.B., University of Minnesota, St. Paul, MN 55108, United States; Atlas, E.L., University of Miami, Miami, FL 33149, United States; Blake, D.R., University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States; Blake, N.J., University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States; Diskin, G.S., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States; Holloway, J.S., NOAA, CSD, Boulder, CO 80305, United States; Hudman, R.C., University of California, Berkeley, CA 94720, United States; Meinardi, S., University of California, Irvine, CA 92697, United States; Ryerson, T.B., NOAA, CSD, Boulder, CO 80305, United States; Sachse, G.W., NASA Langley Research Center, Hampton, VA 23681, United States","We use recent aircraft measurements of a comprehensive suite of anthropogenic halocarbons, carbon monoxide (CO), and related tracers to place new constraints on North American halocarbon emissions and quantifytheir global warming potential. Using a chemical transport model (GEOS-Chem) we find that the ensemble of observations are consistent with our prior best estimate of the U.S. anthropogenic CO source, but suggest a 30% underestimate of Mexican emissions. We develop an optimized CO emission inventory on this basis and quantify halocarbon emissions from their measured enhancements relative to CO. Emissions continue for many compounds restricted under the Montreal Protocol, and we show that halocarbons make up an important fraction of the total greenhouse gas source for both countries: our best estimate is 9% (uncertainty range 6-12%) and 32% (21-52%) of equivalent CO 2 emissions for the U.S. and Mexico, respectively, on a 20 year time scale. Performance of bottom-up emission inventories is variable, with underestimates for some compounds and overestimates for others. Ongoing methylchloroform emissions are significant in the U.S. (2.8 Gg/y in 2004-2006), in contrast to bottom-up estimates (&lt;0.05 Gg), with implications for tropospheric OH calculations. Mexican methylchloroform emissions are minor. © 2009 American Chemical Society.",,"Aircraft measurements; Best estimates; Chemical transport models; CO emissions; Emission inventories; Global warming potentials; Green house gas; Halocarbons; Me-xico; Montreal protocols; North americans; Time-scale; Aircraft; Gas emissions; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Leakage (fluid); Uncertainty analysis; Carbon monoxide; 1,1,1 trichloroethane; carbon monoxide; halocarbon; airborne survey; aircraft; anthropogenic source; atmospheric transport; carbon dioxide; chloroform; emission; emission inventory; global warming; greenhouse gas; halocarbon; troposphere; anthropology; article; greenhouse effect; greenhouse gas; Mexico; North America; troposphere; United States; Air Pollutants; Carbon Monoxide; Chlorofluorocarbons; Greenhouse Effect; Hydrocarbons, Halogenated; Hydroxyl Radical; Mexico; Trichloroethanes; United States; Canada; Mexico [North America]; Montreal; North America; Quebec [Canada]",,"1,1,1 trichloroethane, 71-55-6; carbon monoxide, 630-08-0; 1,1,1-trichloroethane, 71-55-6; 1,1-dichloro-1-fluoroethane, 1717-00-6; Air Pollutants; Carbon Monoxide, 630-08-0; Chlorofluorocarbons; Hydrocarbons, Halogenated; Hydroxyl Radical, 3352-5